<subSubSection id="8FAA1E8DFFBFFF8CFD49260FFC998F50" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" type="description">
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFBFFF8CFD49260FFB8A8C7A" blockId="44.[670,1199,963,1763]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">
IDENTIFICATION: Descriptions and comparative measurements of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBFFF8CFC5E2629FBF48D69" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[940,1151,1083,1106]" class="Mammalia" family="Noctilionidae" genus="Noctilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leporinus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFC5E2629FBF48D69" box="[940,1151,1083,1106]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Noctilio leporinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found in 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFBFFF8CFCC0264AFC518D54" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[818,986,1112,1135]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978) and Davis (1973). Davis recognized three subspecies in his revision: 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFCC82686FCC68D90" box="[826,845,1172,1195]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFCAD2686FCEC8D90" box="[863,871,1172,1195]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">l</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFC8B2686FC548D90" box="[889,991,1172,1195]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">mastivus</emphasis>
(Mexico and the southernmost Bahamas south to western Ecuador and Venezuela), 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFC1026C2FC7E8DDC" box="[994,1013,1232,1255]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFBE126C2FB908DDC" box="[1043,1051,1232,1255]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">l</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBFFF8CFBCA26C2FB258DDC" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1080,1198,1232,1255]" class="Mammalia" family="Noctilionidae" genus="Noctilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leporinus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFBCA26C2FB258DDC" box="[1080,1198,1232,1255]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">leporinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Guianas and eastern Ecuador to eastern Brazil), and 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFCF7271EFC938C18" box="[773,792,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFCD5271EFCA48C18" box="[807,815,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">l</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFCCC271EFC278C18" box="[830,940,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">rufescens</emphasis>
(Bolivia and southern Brazil to northern Argentina).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFBFFF8CFD492755FC998F50" blockId="44.[670,1199,963,1763]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">
Our Paracou vouchers conform with Davis’ (1973) description of the nominate subspecies and are similar in size to specimens previously reported from Surinam. These Guianan specimens are among the smallest known representatives of the species (Davis, 1973), one of our vouchers (MNHN 1995.863) having the smallest body weight (44.5 g) yet recorded for an adult 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBFFF8CFBA22425FC878F50" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Noctilionidae" genus="Noctilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leporinus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBFFF8CFBA22425FC878F50" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Noctilio leporinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FAA1E8DFFBFFF8CFD492460FBBA8FD8" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFBFFF8CFD492460FBBA8FD8" blockId="44.[670,1199,963,1763]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">FIELD OBSERVATIONS: All three specimens that we captured at Paracou were taken in ground­level mistnets set across a small stream (fig. 14) in primary forest.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
